description.text:
- Fixes #102724

Ok, that was a tricky problem!! After commetted most of the code in `display_server_windows.cpp` and `embedded_process.cpp` and still reproducing the issue, I found out the cause of the problem!! The problem was caused by the fact that the input queues of the editor and the game window were on the same thread. I still don't understand why the issue was visible only when trying to move the floating window, but detaching these input queues fixed the issue.

The reel fix is the addition of these lines in `display_server_windows.cpp`:
```cpp
if (p_parent_hwnd) {
	DWORD mainThreadId = GetWindowThreadProcessId(owner_hwnd, nullptr);
	DWORD embeddedThreadId = GetCurrentThreadId();
	AttachThreadInput(embeddedThreadId, mainThreadId, FALSE);
}
```

The other modifications come from some side effects of the modification. Turns out, that detaching the input queue make the floating window a lot more responsive, causing to see some issues with the starting location passed to the embedded game when using the Floating Window.

### Tested versions

4.3 stable with Mono support

### System information

Godot 4.3 C#, Steamdeck with latest SteamOS

### Issue description

My game is using Viewport scaling with keep aspect ratio on, and renders at 1920x1080 resolution. I'm also using hardware mouse cursor and move it around with `GetViewport().WarpMouse(...)` to move it using arrows / joystick on Steamdeck.

When I launch the game on Steamdeck, the cursor will only go as far as the 1280x800 point. Which is the default Steamdeck resolution. See the reference image (not to scale, but gives you the idea based on the text labels hopefully)

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/061f035e-8259-43f7-978b-37f9a72266d8)

The way to solve it is to select Properties in Steamdeck for the game, and change the resolution from "default" to "1920x1080" - however this is a manual step required by the users, and ideally the mouse should work properly when the game renders at smaller resolution and extrapolate the position so that point 1280x800 of hardware mouse is correctly treated as 1920x1080 in the screen space.

This issue does not repro on the PC -> if I resize the window to 1280x800, the mouse can still be moved with keyboard arrows to reach the bottom right corner.

### Steps to reproduce

Create a new project, set the Display size to 1920x1080. Set the scaling mode to Viewport and enable aspect ratio.

Add single ColorRect, name it "InputMouse".

Add the code in _process:
```
float speed = 3;
var mouse_rel = Vector2.Zero;
if (Input.IsActionPressed("ui_up"))
				mouse_rel += Vector2.Up * speed;
if (Input.IsActionPressed("ui_down"))
				mouse_rel += Vector2.Down * speed;
if (Input.IsActionPressed("ui_right"))
				mouse_rel += Vector2.Right * speed;
if (Input.IsActionPressed("ui_left"))
				mouse_rel += Vector2.Left * speed;
if (mouse_rel != Vector2.Zero)
{
				GetViewport().WarpMouse(GetViewport().GetMousePosition() + mouse_rel);

}
GetNode<ColorRect>("InputMouse").Position = GetViewport().GetMousePosition();
```

Build and deploy on Steamdeck - notice that the mouse cursor only reaches 1280x800.

